orting, and constant influence of the Holy Ghost.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"o9q7AXGVGx"}],"key":"YZu0LNw1ho"}],"key":"XQyBePI052"}],"key":"lakpoho8pJ"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Process Safety","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"bVIp5gFmvD"}],"identifier":"process-safety","label":"Process Safety","html_id":"process-safety","implicit":true,"key":"moWkpAMQOv"}],"key":"THZ3Y4a63R"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Safety Culture","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"xUP2lAYZHw"}],"identifier":"safety-culture","label":"Safety Culture","html_id":"safety-culture","implicit":true,"key":"t9ViDdY9hq"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How important is safety to you and those around you? What does process safety mean? What does it mean to your company? Are you willing to work for a company that does not value safety? Is it true that a company that does not value safety does not value you?","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"MdM6ANS17S"}],"key":"Tr80e9WuZn"}],"key":"rJur0nAVpe"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Ultimately, we are responsible for our safety, both physical and spiritual. We’ll talk about many accidents in the course. For example, a few days ago, the Los Angeles Times reported about Zuko Carrasco, who was paralyzed while leading people on a trust fall. He blames himself as he was the last to descend when what he thought he heard was “on belay” but his belayer was not yet ready. He jumped and fell 40 feet and was paralyzed from the waist down. He had safely completed that activity many times before.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"ligWKfTbbZ"}],"key":"tvq1Rw5Ykq"}],"key":"GqXvGAOCwn"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Voluntary and Involuntary Risk","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"RiQFbTk12w"}],"identifier":"voluntary-and-involuntary-risk","label":"Voluntary and Involuntary Risk","html_id":"voluntary-and-involuntary-risk","implicit":true,"key":"chXlw0TNBR"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Most are much more comfortable assuming voluntary versus involuntary risk. As a chemical engineer, how will you mitigate those two types of risk? Undoubtedly, a chemical engineer will work under voluntary risk and be on the front lines of helping to reduce involuntary risk to the public.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"ciXiI4v3d1"}],"key":"CiLcDVVUNL"}],"key":"LGufEX6fsc"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Safety Metrics","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"chhzcziGgQ"}],"identifier":"safety-metrics","label":"Safety Metrics","html_id":"safety-metrics","implicit":true,"key":"r8Ro8gXxnI"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You say you’re safe...prove 